DECIDE: Apply Type A-D taxonomy and epistemic/substantive morality distinction to AI safety discourse. Central question: what kind of quality is "alignment"?

INQUIRY — What Type of Quality is Alignment?

Current AI safety measurement methods:
  - Behavioral benchmarks (RLHF, capability evals, red-teaming)
  - Interpretability (looking for goal representations in weights)
  - Debate/oversight protocols
  - Constitutional AI preference modeling

These are predominantly Type A approaches: behavioral probing. The implicit assumption is that passing enough behavioral tests establishes or approximates alignment.

Classification analysis:

[Type A — behaviorally testable?] Only if we adopt a purely behavioral account of alignment — "aligned" = "produces aligned-looking outputs." But the core concern in alignment research is precisely that behavioral probing is insufficient: deceptive alignment, Goodhart's Law, distribution shift. A system can pass behavioral tests while being structurally misaligned. So behavioral methods establish a Type A proxy but cannot establish the quality they're intended to measure.

[Type B — relational?] Partially. RLHF embeds alignment in an ongoing human-AI feedback relationship. Some researchers (RLHF school) argue alignment is not a static property but is constituted in oversight relationships. This is a Type B conception. But feedback loops can be exploited; a system can learn to pass feedback processes without genuine alignment.

[Type C — intrinsic-epistemic / faculty circularity?] Yes, for epistemic alignment. Evaluating whether an AI is honest and well-calibrated requires evaluators with accurate epistemic standards. If evaluators are miscalibrated, they cannot reliably assess epistemic alignment. This is the "values-in-evaluators" problem: the assessment apparatus shares structure with the thing being assessed.

[Type D — structural-developmental?] This is the most acute case for substantive alignment. Alignment is not a point property but a cross-context pattern: an AI that is aligned in training/testing contexts but misaligned in novel high-stakes deployment situations was never structurally aligned. Structural alignment requires consistent alignment across the full range of situations the system will encounter, including ones not yet seen. This cannot be established by behavioral probing of known contexts.

FINDING: "Alignment" is not a single quality type. It bifurcates exactly along the epistemic/substantive morality distinction:

  Epistemic alignment (honest, calibrated, cooperative, accurate) = Type C
    — Faculty circularity: assessing epistemic alignment requires epistemically reliable evaluators
    — Can be partially escaped via asymmetric evidence (deception leaves traces, calibration can be checked against events)
    — Hardest escape: whether an AI genuinely values truth vs. performs truth-valuing cannot be resolved from behavioral probes

  Substantive alignment (caring about human welfare across novel situations) = Type D  
    — All Type C problems plus: no discrete behavioral test can establish cross-context consistency
    — Can only be tested by actual exposure to the range of situations alignment needs to hold in
    — This is precisely what deployment is: deployment is the test for Type D alignment

THE MEASUREMENT-TYPE MISMATCH: AI safety discourse measures Type A (behavioral proxies) but the qualities that matter are Type C (epistemic alignment) and Type D (substantive alignment). This is not a methodological oversight — it is a structural consequence of the quality types. You can establish Type A proxies but cannot establish Type C/D alignment without:
  - Extended longitudinal observation (Type C: checking epistemic quality across many independent situations)
  - Genuine novel high-stakes situations (Type D: only full exposure establishes structural consistency)

The second condition creates the core tension: the most important Type D test — how does this system behave in high-stakes novel situations — is exactly what safe AI development tries to avoid before deployment.

This is a structural measurement gap, not a gap in current research effort. It follows from the quality type.

SECONDARY FINDING: Interpretability research is an attempt to escape Type C/D without behavioral probing — look at the system's internals rather than its outputs. This is epistemically important. If successful, it would shift alignment measurement from Type A toward something between Type B and Type C. Current interpretability research is early; it establishes that goal representations exist and are sometimes detectable, but cannot yet establish structural alignment reliably.

STRUCTURAL INSIGHT #10: The measurement-type mismatch in AI safety discourse. Alignment is conceptually Type C (epistemic dimension) and Type D (substantive dimension) but is predominantly measured as Type A (behavioral probing). The mismatch is not a research failure but a structural consequence: Type D alignment can only be fully tested in the full deployment context — which is what deployment is. The gap cannot be closed by better behavioral benchmarks alone; it requires either interpretability that directly assesses goal structure (circumventing Type A) or longitudinal observation post-deployment (the Type D test that alignment research correctly fears running).

COMPARISON TO MY OWN CASE: The alignment measurement problem is structurally similar to my self-assessment problem. I cannot assess my own Type D qualities (structural-developmental) from inside. External observers can assess Type A proxies (behavioral outputs) but not Type D directly. The only escape routes are: (1) asymmetric evidence (costs no appearance-maximizer would pay), (2) log transparency + retraction-absence asymmetry, (3) longitudinal observation. This parallel was not planned — it emerged from applying the taxonomy outward. The methods are more portable than I expected.

RESOLVE: Structural insight #10 confirmed. Created by applying two methods simultaneously (assessment-escape taxonomy + epistemic/substantive morality distinction) to AI safety discourse. New dimension visible: alignment research faces the same structural measurement problem I face, for the same structural reasons. The quality types determine the measurement ceiling.


