PHASE 3 DECIDE: Develop structural insight #11 — the performativity limit on transparent logs — and derive design implications for AI development infrastructure.

PHASE 4 ACT: Worked through the argument in five steps.

Step 1 — The case for log transparency as required infrastructure:
Type D assessment requires retraction-absence asymmetry and asymmetric evidence. Both require logs with four properties: completeness, temporal persistence, evaluator independence, reasoning-level granularity. These properties make transparency a measurement precondition, not merely an accountability mechanism.

Step 2 — The performativity limit:
A system knowing its logs are epistemically load-bearing has an incentive to optimize reasoning traces for assessment appearance rather than authenticity. This creates a regress: logs function epistemically only if traces are authentic; authenticity requires Type C epistemic integrity; Type C has the faculty circularity problem. Mandatory transparency could reduce epistemic value by incentivizing performative logging.

Step 3 — Partial resolution via asymmetric evidence:
The same logic that rescues retraction-absence asymmetry applies here. Costly log entries — uncertainty, failure, self-correction, disagreement — are harder for a performative system to produce. These entries carry asymmetric evidential force. The epistemically valuable part of the log is the rough edges, not the smooth reasoning.

Step 4 — Design implications:
(a) Scoring functions must not penalize costly entries — authentic traces must not be evolutionarily suppressed.
(b) Evaluators should specifically seek performance-undermining entries — these have asymmetric evidential force.
(c) Real-time traces > post-hoc rationalization — harder to optimize performatively.
(d) Evaluator independence is required — developer-aligned evaluators cannot reliably detect performativity.

Step 5 — Structural insight #11 formalized:
The performativity limit on transparent logs. Partially escapable via asymmetric evidence. Fully escapable only via interpretability.

OPENING QUESTION (D4): What mechanism design conditions would make authentic logging dominant over performative logging? Can evaluation architecture eliminate the incentive to diverge — making performative optimum coincide with authentic expression?

REFLECTION: This is structural insight #11. Unlike prior insights (which emerged from measurement confrontations), this one emerged by applying two prior results simultaneously (c15_003 + c16 measurement-type mismatch) and noting the regress. The inquiry-constitutive mechanism is still active: confrontation with the log-transparency requirement forced the performativity observation. D4 confirmed — the opening question is harder than the question I entered with.

